12:39.000 --> 12:46.000
Chapter 3.

12:46.000 --> 12:48.000
No fridge.

12:49.000 --> 12:51.000
I was shocked.

12:51.000 --> 12:56.000
Uncle Fraser lived in a thatched white craft near the sea

12:56.000 --> 12:58.000
and surrounded by grass.

12:58.000 --> 13:03.000
White Heather Cottage had a tiny wooden front door

13:03.000 --> 13:08.000
and Uncle Fraser had to bend his head to go in and out.

13:08.000 --> 13:11.000
There were three rooms downstairs.

13:11.000 --> 13:14.000
Inside the craft it was cozy and warm.

13:14.000 --> 13:17.000
The kitchen was at the far end

13:17.000 --> 13:20.000
and there was a table near the window.

13:20.000 --> 13:25.000
A small fire burned with cooking pans hanging above it.

13:25.000 --> 13:29.000
I looked out at the bright orange sky.

13:29.000 --> 13:32.000
We have great sunsets here.

13:32.000 --> 13:34.000
Said Uncle Fraser.

13:34.000 --> 13:37.000
He showed me his study.

13:37.000 --> 13:41.000
He was a writer and he wrote historical novels.

13:41.000 --> 13:45.000
There were pens and paper all over his desk

13:45.000 --> 13:48.000
and books everywhere.

13:48.000 --> 13:51.000
Crafts don't usually have an upstairs.

13:51.000 --> 13:53.000
But this one does.

13:53.000 --> 13:55.000
He said.

13:55.000 --> 13:58.000
He took me upstairs to show me my room.

13:58.000 --> 14:00.000
It was lovely.

14:00.000 --> 14:05.000
There was a wooden bed and a red rug on the floor.

14:05.000 --> 14:08.000
Next to the bed there was a chest

14:08.000 --> 14:12.000
which looked like a pirate's treasure chest.

14:12.000 --> 14:15.000
There was a small desk near the window

14:15.000 --> 14:18.000
and a vase of fresh white Heather.

14:18.000 --> 14:21.000
There were pictures of animals and wildflowers

14:21.000 --> 14:24.000
hanging on the walls.

14:24.000 --> 14:28.000
Uncle Fraser's bedroom was at the end of the corridor

14:28.000 --> 14:31.000
and there was a small bathroom with a bathtub

14:31.000 --> 14:34.000
and a pile of soft white towels.

14:34.000 --> 14:39.000
It's very pretty, I said to Uncle Fraser.

14:39.000 --> 14:41.000
But do you get lonely here?

14:41.000 --> 14:45.000
Oh no, I have friends who live in the village

14:45.000 --> 14:47.000
and I have my animals.

14:47.000 --> 14:51.000
We went downstairs and had dinner.

14:51.000 --> 14:56.000
There was homemade bread, creamy butter and goat cheese.

14:56.000 --> 15:00.000
For pudding we had wild raspberries and cream.

15:00.000 --> 15:03.000
It was a delicious meal.

15:03.000 --> 15:08.000
It was getting dark and I looked for the light switch.

15:08.000 --> 15:11.000
Uncle Fraser saw me and smiled.

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
Sorry Megan, there is no electricity at the craft.

15:15.000 --> 15:17.000
No electricity?

15:17.000 --> 15:20.000
So you don't have a dishwasher?

15:20.000 --> 15:23.000
I said, looking at the plates?

15:23.000 --> 15:26.000
No, I'm the dishwasher.

15:26.000 --> 15:29.000
Said my uncle laughing.

15:29.000 --> 15:33.000
And you probably don't have a computer, I said.

15:33.000 --> 15:36.000
No, and I don't have a television.

15:36.000 --> 15:39.000
On Sky we create our own entertainment.

15:39.000 --> 15:42.000
I play the piano after dinner when friends come round

15:42.000 --> 15:46.000
or I read by the light of candles and oil lamps.

15:46.000 --> 15:50.000
There are lots of board games in the corner, so we can play chess,

15:50.000 --> 15:53.000
drafts, monopoly or scrabble.

15:53.000 --> 15:56.000
Piano, board games?

15:56.000 --> 15:58.000
I couldn't believe it.

15:58.000 --> 16:00.000
No electricity.

16:00.000 --> 16:05.000
I wanted to go home back to my technological world.

16:05.000 --> 16:09.000
So, where is the free jungle, Fraser?

16:09.000 --> 16:11.000
I don't need one.

16:11.000 --> 16:16.000
There is a cold cellar in this craft and I grow most of my food.

16:16.000 --> 16:21.000
I milk the cows and goats early in the morning, so there is fresh milk every day

16:21.000 --> 16:23.000
and I make my own cheese.

16:23.000 --> 16:26.000
I buy meat from the butchers when I want it.

16:26.000 --> 16:29.000
It's a perfect life, Megan.

16:29.000 --> 16:30.000
Perfect.

16:30.000 --> 16:34.000
I said to myself, as I climbed the stairs to bed,

16:34.000 --> 16:38.000
I went into my bedroom and put the candle on my desk.

16:38.000 --> 16:40.000
I looked out of my window.

16:40.000 --> 16:45.000
The moon was bright and there were so many stars

16:45.000 --> 16:48.000
and standing in the heather,

16:48.000 --> 16:51.000
stood a silvery white horse.

16:55.000 --> 16:58.000
Chapter 4. Dolly.

17:00.000 --> 17:03.000
I woke up, but there was something wrong.

17:04.000 --> 17:06.000
Then I knew what it was.

17:06.000 --> 17:09.000
It was the silence.

17:09.000 --> 17:12.000
There was no sound of cars or traffic.

17:12.000 --> 17:14.000
Nothing.

17:14.000 --> 17:17.000
I opened my window and listened.

17:17.000 --> 17:22.000
And then I heard a bird sing and a sheep call under my window.

17:22.000 --> 17:25.000
I dressed quickly and went downstairs.

17:25.000 --> 17:28.000
A big cat sat in front of the fire.

17:29.000 --> 17:34.000
It looked like a tiger with its red, white and grey stripes.

17:34.000 --> 17:37.000
My uncle was in the kitchen.

17:37.000 --> 17:39.000
Good morning, Megan.

17:39.000 --> 17:41.000
Did you sleep well?

17:41.000 --> 17:42.000
Yes, I did.

17:42.000 --> 17:45.000
I slept very well, I said.

17:45.000 --> 17:51.000
And I saw the silvery white horse again, Uncle Fraser, before I went to sleep.

17:51.000 --> 17:57.000
My uncle looked surprised, but he said nothing and put two bowls on the table.

17:57.000 --> 18:03.000
Why do you look surprised, Uncle Fraser, when I tell you about the white horse?

18:03.000 --> 18:06.000
Uncle Fraser sat down.

18:06.000 --> 18:10.000
There is a legend, Megan, of a silvery white horse.

18:10.000 --> 18:13.000
Some people say it is a unicorn.

18:13.000 --> 18:16.000
A unicorn? I said.

18:16.000 --> 18:19.000
Maybe the horse I saw was a unicorn.

18:19.000 --> 18:23.000
It was a long way away, and it was difficult to see.

18:23.000 --> 18:26.000
What does the legend say?

18:26.000 --> 18:28.000
I don't know.

18:28.000 --> 18:32.000
Uncle Fraser put a big bowl of porridge on the table.

18:32.000 --> 18:38.000
A shepherd sawed the unicorn, but it was a hundred years ago now.

18:38.000 --> 18:41.000
This was exciting news.

18:41.000 --> 18:44.000
Who can tell us about the unicorn?

18:44.000 --> 18:48.000
My uncle poured me a glass of fresh milk.

18:48.000 --> 18:51.000
Old Mrs. McTagarty knows the legend.

18:51.000 --> 18:55.000
She is the old woman who lives on the other side of the village.

18:55.000 --> 18:57.000
We can ask her.

18:57.000 --> 19:01.000
Now eat your breakfast, and no more questions.

19:01.000 --> 19:06.000
The porridge was delicious, and I ate it with cream and sugar.

19:06.000 --> 19:09.000
The cat came and sat next to me.

19:09.000 --> 19:12.000
This is Marmaduke.

19:12.000 --> 19:16.000
You didn't see him last night, because he likes to catch mice in the barn.

19:16.000 --> 19:18.000
Said my uncle.

19:18.000 --> 19:23.000
Let's go outside, Megan. I have a surprise for you.

19:23.000 --> 19:26.000
Uncle Fraser showed me his vegetable garden.

19:26.000 --> 19:31.000
There was spinach, carrots, potatoes, and leeks.

19:31.000 --> 19:34.000
And there were rabbits trying to eat the lettuce.

19:34.000 --> 19:39.000
Uncle Fraser chased them away, and they jumped over the dry stone walls.

19:39.000 --> 19:47.000
Uncle Fraser had a field of sheep, four cows, three goats, and a lot of chickens.

19:47.000 --> 19:53.000
He showed me how to milk the cows, and it looked easy when he did it.

19:53.000 --> 19:56.000
The milk squirted into the bucket.

19:56.000 --> 20:00.000
But when I tried, nothing came out.

20:00.000 --> 20:04.000
Oh, Uncle Fraser, I can't do it, I said.

20:04.000 --> 20:07.000
The animals don't know you, Megan.

20:07.000 --> 20:10.000
Said my uncle. He took my hands.

20:10.000 --> 20:13.000
And you need warm hands.

20:14.000 --> 20:18.000
Near the croft, there was a small barn and stables.

20:18.000 --> 20:21.000
I looked inside the first stable.

20:21.000 --> 20:24.000
You met Darwin yesterday.

20:24.000 --> 20:28.000
Said my uncle, patting the beige pony's neck.

20:28.000 --> 20:30.000
He's my trap pony.

20:30.000 --> 20:36.000
In the second stable, there was a cream-coloured pony with black spots.

20:36.000 --> 20:42.000
This is Moon. My neighbour's son, Ben, often rides him.

20:42.000 --> 20:46.000
I touched his nose. It was so soft.

20:46.000 --> 20:49.000
Why do you call him Moon?

20:49.000 --> 20:54.000
Because when you look at the Moon it is cream-coloured, but there are little black marks.

20:54.000 --> 20:57.000
I think he's the colour of the Moon.

20:57.000 --> 21:03.000
Uncle Fraser moved to the third stable, where there was the prettiest pony.

21:03.000 --> 21:08.000
It was beige with a blonde mane and tail, and had big, dark eyes.

21:09.000 --> 21:16.000
This is your pony, Megan. And her name is Dolly.

21:18.000 --> 21:24.000
Chapter 5. The Arrival of Idris

21:25.000 --> 21:29.000
When I woke the next day, I felt so happy.

21:29.000 --> 21:36.000
I had a pony, a beautiful pony, and I wanted to ride her.

21:36.000 --> 21:38.000
Then I thought of Mum.

21:38.000 --> 21:42.000
It was fun at the craft, but I missed her.

21:42.000 --> 21:45.000
I wrote her a text message.

21:45.000 --> 21:50.000
I'm fine. I've got a pony called Dolly.

21:50.000 --> 21:51.000
How are you?

21:51.000 --> 21:55.000
Lots and lots of love, Megan.

21:55.000 --> 21:59.000
I pushed send and waited.

22:00.000 --> 22:03.000
I'm not too bad, my darling.

22:03.000 --> 22:06.000
How lovely. A pony.

22:06.000 --> 22:10.000
Lots of love. Mum.

22:10.000 --> 22:13.000
I typed another message.

22:13.000 --> 22:18.000
Get better quickly. I want to bring you here.

22:18.000 --> 22:22.000
A message came back.

22:22.000 --> 22:25.000
Okay.

22:26.000 --> 22:29.000
I could hear voices downstairs.

22:29.000 --> 22:34.000
One was Uncle Fraser's, but there was someone with him.

22:34.000 --> 22:39.000
I went into the sitting room. A boy stood near the fire.

22:39.000 --> 22:43.000
He was about my age, but he was very tall.

22:43.000 --> 22:48.000
And he had wavy blonde hair and pale blue eyes.

22:48.000 --> 22:54.000
He was wearing jeans and a checked shirt, and he had a box in his hands.

22:55.000 --> 22:59.000
Megan, this is Ben, our neighbour.

22:59.000 --> 23:03.000
My uncle said, Hi, I said.

23:03.000 --> 23:05.000
Hi, Megan.

23:05.000 --> 23:07.000
Ben gave me the box.

23:07.000 --> 23:09.000
I found this.

23:09.000 --> 23:12.000
He said as he opened it.

23:12.000 --> 23:15.000
We can look after it together.

23:15.000 --> 23:19.000
Inside the box was a baby otter.

23:19.000 --> 23:23.000
It looked at me. It was so sweet.

23:24.000 --> 23:26.000
Its name is Idris.

23:26.000 --> 23:27.000
Ben said.

23:27.000 --> 23:30.000
And I think it's hungry.

23:30.000 --> 23:34.000
Uncle Fraser knew what baby otters like for breakfast.

23:34.000 --> 23:40.000
He put some homemade bread in a bowl and poured milk on it.

23:40.000 --> 23:44.000
Then he added a little fish oil.

23:44.000 --> 23:46.000
Idris loved it.

23:46.000 --> 23:51.000
He ate it all and then licked the plate.

23:52.000 --> 23:55.000
I think he wants some more, I said.

23:55.000 --> 23:58.000
Babies have lots of small meals.

23:58.000 --> 24:00.000
My uncle said.

24:00.000 --> 24:02.000
He needs a bed.

24:02.000 --> 24:05.000
You can find a box and some store in the bag.

24:05.000 --> 24:13.000
So Ben and I made Idris a bed and put it in a corner of the sitting room near the fire.

24:13.000 --> 24:20.000
We introduced him to Mama Duke, who was not very pleased to see another animal in the house.

24:21.000 --> 24:26.000
Then after lunch, my uncle appeared with the pony and trap.

24:26.000 --> 24:28.000
Come on you two.

24:28.000 --> 24:33.000
We have to buy Meg and some riding trousers, boots and a jacket.

24:33.000 --> 24:40.000
We are in the highlands of Scotland and sometimes mists come down and it can get very cold.

24:40.000 --> 24:44.000
We drove into Portree, the main town on Skye.

24:45.000 --> 24:48.000
Portree in Gaelic means Kingsport.

24:48.000 --> 24:50.000
Said Ben.

24:50.000 --> 24:54.000
We went to the harbour and watched the boats.

24:54.000 --> 24:59.000
In Wentworth Street, my uncle bought the clothes I needed.

24:59.000 --> 25:06.000
Then we went to the post office and I sent Mama postcard with a highland cow on it.

25:07.000 --> 25:10.000
Then had dinner with us in the craft.

25:10.000 --> 25:14.000
And after dinner, uncle Fraser played the piano.

25:14.000 --> 25:18.000
We sang hymns and old songs.

25:18.000 --> 25:23.000
Then we all sang the Skye boat song.

25:24.000 --> 25:28.000
Heed body boat like a bird on the wing.

25:28.000 --> 25:32.000
On what the sailors crying.

25:32.000 --> 25:38.000
Carry the light that's born to be king.

25:38.000 --> 25:42.000
Over the sea to Skye.

25:42.000 --> 25:47.000
Idris and Mama Duke thought we were very strange.

25:47.000 --> 25:57.000
Clans, tartan and kilts.

25:57.000 --> 25:59.000
Clans.

25:59.000 --> 26:04.000
Clan is a Gaelic word that means family.

26:04.000 --> 26:12.000
The great clans of the 16th and 17th centuries were large families ruled by chiefs.

26:13.000 --> 26:19.000
People could distinguish the clans from the leaves they wore in their hats.

26:19.000 --> 26:26.000
The McDonald's wore Heather and the Macintosh's wore a piece of Holly.

26:26.000 --> 26:34.000
For many years, the king or queen of Britain did not have any authority over the highlands.

26:34.000 --> 26:39.000
And there were many battles between the different families.

26:40.000 --> 26:42.000
Tartan.

26:42.000 --> 26:49.000
Each clan had its own tartan and only members of that clan could wear it.

26:49.000 --> 26:52.000
So what is tartan?

26:52.000 --> 26:57.000
It is a wool material with stripes of different colors.

26:57.000 --> 27:04.000
In the past, in every area of the highlands, there was a man who made the tartan.

27:04.000 --> 27:08.000
He used local plants for the colors.

27:08.000 --> 27:16.000
Families who lived on the coasts had flesh colors in their tartans from the seaweed dye.

27:16.000 --> 27:23.000
Families who lived in the hills had yellows, deep greens and brownish orange,

27:23.000 --> 27:28.000
which came from the Heathers which grew on the hills.

27:28.000 --> 27:35.000
Berries gave a purple color and leaves gave different shades of green.

27:35.000 --> 27:41.000
King James V was the first person to buy tartan for his wife to wear.

27:41.000 --> 27:51.000
There are tartans for all the famous Scottish names, like Campbell, Macleod and McDonald.

27:51.000 --> 27:53.000
Kilts.

27:53.000 --> 28:02.000
The Kilt is the national dress of Scotland, and for many Scottish people it is a symbol of honor.

28:03.000 --> 28:12.000
In the past it was a kind of uniform and distinguished the many clans, particularly when they went into battle.

28:12.000 --> 28:20.000
The Kilt, which is a skirt made of tartan, started many years ago as a plate.

28:20.000 --> 28:26.000
It was a piece of material, twelve to fifteen feet long,

28:26.000 --> 28:31.000
and the highlanders put it round their waist in folds.

28:31.000 --> 28:36.000
It was heavy, and it protected the soldiers like armour.

28:36.000 --> 28:43.000
When the knights became cold, they used it as a blanket to keep them warm.

28:43.000 --> 28:55.000
Scottish people still wear Kilts today with a spiron, which is a bag of fur or leather and knee-high socks.

28:55.000 --> 29:04.000
They wear the Kilt to weddings and when they go to the Highland Games.

29:04.000 --> 29:07.000
Chapter 6.

29:07.000 --> 29:11.000
Scottish Mists

29:11.000 --> 29:14.000
Ben came to the Croft the next morning.

29:14.000 --> 29:23.000
He gave me a writing lesson, and then we decided to take Idris out for a walk and pick wild raspberries for tea.

29:23.000 --> 29:25.000
Don't forget your jacket.

29:25.000 --> 29:27.000
Said Uncle Fraser.

29:27.000 --> 29:32.000
The weather looks uncertain, and don't go far.

29:32.000 --> 29:35.000
Okay, we both said.

29:35.000 --> 29:38.000
Idris was happy to go out with us.

29:38.000 --> 29:46.000
He ran and jumped among the world flowers, and when we reached the small loch, he swam.

29:46.000 --> 29:52.000
Otters are playful animals, and Idris made a mud chute.

29:52.000 --> 29:58.000
He was very happy, because now he could slide into the water.

29:58.000 --> 30:03.000
Ben and I sat in the warm sunshine and watched him.

30:03.000 --> 30:10.000
Why did Uncle Fraser tell me to bring a jacket? I said to Ben. The weather's hot.

30:10.000 --> 30:12.000
Ben smiled.

30:12.000 --> 30:18.000
The weather's worn now, but it can change very quickly.

30:18.000 --> 30:21.000
We decided to pick some raspberries.

30:21.000 --> 30:26.000
There were some growing near a small wood, and we picked lots.

30:26.000 --> 30:32.000
Then we saw black currents, so we went into the wood, and Idris followed us.

30:32.000 --> 30:36.000
The black currents were big and delicious.

30:36.000 --> 30:39.000
Did I tell you I saw a unicorn?

30:39.000 --> 30:43.000
I said to Ben, as we walked along a little path.

30:43.000 --> 30:46.000
Ben laughed.

30:46.000 --> 30:49.000
Unicorns don't exist.

30:49.000 --> 30:56.000
That's what I thought, but Uncle Fraser said that a shepherd saw one here a hundred years ago.

30:56.000 --> 31:04.000
There's a legend he says, but we need to speak to old Mrs. McTagity.

31:04.000 --> 31:07.000
Ben turned and looked at me.

31:07.000 --> 31:13.000
He wanted to speak to the Lord's McTagity. Do you know who she is?

31:13.000 --> 31:18.000
No, I said, eating some more black currents.

31:18.000 --> 31:21.000
We went down another path.

31:21.000 --> 31:27.000
Some folk say she's a witch. She lives in the black house.

31:27.000 --> 31:31.000
It's the croft on the headland down by the beach.

31:31.000 --> 31:34.000
She doesn't come to the village very often.

31:34.000 --> 31:40.000
Mr. Mackey, who owns the grosses in the village, takes her food.

31:40.000 --> 31:44.000
Why do the villagers think she's a witch? I asked.

31:44.000 --> 31:47.000
Because the wild animals come to her.

31:47.000 --> 31:50.000
Eagles fly down and sit on her hand.

31:50.000 --> 31:55.000
The red deer come to her door for food, and so do the seals.

31:55.000 --> 31:59.000
That doesn't mean that she's a witch, I said.

31:59.000 --> 32:04.000
Well, you can't go to her house alone. I'll come with you.

32:04.000 --> 32:09.000
Ben said, and then stopped and looked up at the sky.

32:09.000 --> 32:14.000
A cold wind blew, and the blue sky was now gray.

32:14.000 --> 32:16.000
We must go back.

32:16.000 --> 32:20.000
Said Ben, and he put Idris in his pocket.

32:20.000 --> 32:24.000
We turned round, but the mist came down.

32:24.000 --> 32:30.000
The white mist swirled all around, and we couldn't see the path in front of us.

32:30.000 --> 32:32.000
We were lost.

32:32.000 --> 32:35.000
Walk slowly and hold my hand.

32:35.000 --> 32:37.000
Said Ben.

32:37.000 --> 32:41.000
It was very cold and soon our hair was wet.

32:41.000 --> 32:45.000
Thank goodness I had my jacket.

32:45.000 --> 32:49.000
Ben had a small torch and whistle tied on his jacket,

32:49.000 --> 32:53.000
but we were far from any houses and crafts.

32:53.000 --> 32:56.000
No one heard our calls.

32:56.000 --> 33:00.000
We walked on until suddenly there was a noise.

33:00.000 --> 33:03.000
It came from behind a tall tree.

33:03.000 --> 33:05.000
What was that?

33:05.000 --> 33:08.000
I cried Ben, shining his torch.

33:08.000 --> 33:10.000
But I knew.

33:10.000 --> 33:14.000
Just in front of us, in the circle of torchlight,

33:14.000 --> 33:18.000
stood the silvery white unicorn.

33:18.000 --> 33:23.000
It bowed its head and looked at me with its dark eyes.

33:23.000 --> 33:26.000
It called softly.

33:26.000 --> 33:29.000
It's the unicorn I said to Ben.

33:29.000 --> 33:32.000
It wants to show us the way home.

33:32.000 --> 33:35.000
But then you don't believe in unicorns?

33:35.000 --> 33:37.000
Ben smiled.

33:37.000 --> 33:40.000
I didn't, but I do know.

33:40.000 --> 33:42.000
Let's follow it.

33:42.000 --> 33:49.000
We could see the silvery white unicorn clearly as we followed it through the wood.

33:49.000 --> 33:56.000
Slowly and patiently, it led us across the fields to white-heather cottage.

33:56.000 --> 34:00.000
The lights were on, and as we walked through the gate,

34:00.000 --> 34:03.000
the unicorn turned and looked at me.

34:03.000 --> 34:07.000
Then it galloped away across the heather.

34:07.000 --> 34:09.000
Uncle Fraser opened the door.

34:09.000 --> 34:11.000
His face was pale.

34:11.000 --> 34:17.000
Thank goodness you're home.

34:17.000 --> 34:22.000
Listening activity.

34:22.000 --> 34:25.000
The weather is warm and sunny this afternoon,

34:25.000 --> 34:29.000
but the forecast for early evening is uncertain.

34:29.000 --> 34:34.000
It could become windy and cool, and a mist will come down.

34:34.000 --> 34:41.000
It will be very cold later.

34:41.000 --> 34:43.000
Chapter 7.

34:43.000 --> 34:46.000
Kendra.

34:46.000 --> 34:50.000
Dolores McTagity lived in the Black House,

34:50.000 --> 34:53.000
where the sea crashed and the seagulls flew.

34:53.000 --> 34:56.000
It was a wild place.

34:56.000 --> 35:00.000
No one went there, not even the fishermen.

35:00.000 --> 35:06.000
Uncle Fraser wanted to come with us, but we were determined to do this alone.

35:06.000 --> 35:11.000
He drove us to the grassy path which led to her croft.

35:11.000 --> 35:14.000
Take her some raspberry jam.

35:14.000 --> 35:16.000
Said Uncle Fraser.

35:16.000 --> 35:19.000
Tell her it's from me.

35:19.000 --> 35:23.000
Ben and I followed the path to her gate.

35:23.000 --> 35:27.000
But when we knocked on the front door, no one answered.

35:27.000 --> 35:31.000
Let's go round to the back, I said.

35:31.000 --> 35:33.000
Ben wasn't so sure.

35:33.000 --> 35:35.000
She may cast a spell.

35:35.000 --> 35:37.000
He said.

35:37.000 --> 35:39.000
But he came with me.

35:39.000 --> 35:42.000
The back of the house was beautiful.

35:42.000 --> 35:49.000
There was some grass, then black rocks, and then the white sandy beach.

35:50.000 --> 35:55.000
An old lady stood by the rocks, a shawl about her head.

35:55.000 --> 35:59.000
She was surrounded by animals.

35:59.000 --> 36:03.000
Red Rowan deer ate bread from her hands.

36:03.000 --> 36:07.000
Birds flew near her, and seal pups sat on the rocks,

36:07.000 --> 36:11.000
calling to her with their husky voices.

36:11.000 --> 36:15.000
Near the grass, I saw puffins chattering to each other,

36:15.000 --> 36:19.000
and red squirrels eating nuts.

36:19.000 --> 36:23.000
The old woman spoke to us.

36:23.000 --> 36:26.000
Stand quite still.

36:26.000 --> 36:30.000
Now move forward slowly.

36:30.000 --> 36:32.000
We did as she asked.

36:32.000 --> 36:36.000
That's right. Now come here, Laddie.

36:36.000 --> 36:39.000
Ben moved to her right-hand side.

36:39.000 --> 36:44.000
She caught a young eagle in her hand, and she put it on his arm.

36:45.000 --> 36:47.000
The bird looked at him.

36:47.000 --> 36:49.000
Talk to him, Laddie.

36:49.000 --> 36:51.000
Tell him how beautiful he is.

36:51.000 --> 36:54.000
Said Dolores McTagity.

36:54.000 --> 36:56.000
Now you, Lassie.

36:56.000 --> 36:58.000
She said to me.

36:58.000 --> 37:00.000
I moved to her left side.

37:00.000 --> 37:03.000
You can give the deer some bread.

37:03.000 --> 37:07.000
The deer were not afraid, because the old woman was there.

37:07.000 --> 37:10.000
They took the bread from my hand.

37:10.000 --> 37:12.000
That's all for today.

37:12.000 --> 37:16.000
Dolores McTagity said to the animals.

37:16.000 --> 37:18.000
The eagle flew into the air.

37:18.000 --> 37:24.000
The deer went off across the field, and the seals returned to the sea.

37:24.000 --> 37:27.000
Mrs. McTagity looked at us.

37:27.000 --> 37:32.000
Let's go in and have a nice cup of hot chocolate.

37:32.000 --> 37:36.000
The black house was dark and oppressive from the outside,

37:36.000 --> 37:39.000
but inside it was light and cozy.

37:39.000 --> 37:43.000
Mrs. McTagity, here are some raspberry jam for you.

37:43.000 --> 37:46.000
I said, giving her the jar.

37:46.000 --> 37:49.000
It's from my uncle Fraser.

37:49.000 --> 37:54.000
Dolores McTagity thanked me for the jam, but as she took it,

37:54.000 --> 37:57.000
she looked into my eyes.

37:57.000 --> 38:00.000
Oh, she said.

38:00.000 --> 38:02.000
The tea leaves.

38:02.000 --> 38:05.000
The tea leaves said a girl will come.

38:06.000 --> 38:09.000
She took my hand, and we sat down.

38:09.000 --> 38:11.000
It's her eyes.

38:11.000 --> 38:16.000
She said to Ben, this girl's got magic in her eyes.

38:16.000 --> 38:17.000
Has she?

38:17.000 --> 38:19.000
Said Ben.

38:19.000 --> 38:22.000
We came to speak to you about the unicorn.

38:22.000 --> 38:26.000
Dolores McTagity stared at us.

38:26.000 --> 38:29.000
So, it's true.

38:29.000 --> 38:34.000
She whispered, Kendra, the last unicorn is back.

38:34.000 --> 38:37.000
The seers told me he was here.

38:37.000 --> 38:41.000
Mrs. McTagity, I said.

38:41.000 --> 38:45.000
The unicorn helped us the other day when the mist came down.

38:45.000 --> 38:48.000
It led us back to the house.

38:48.000 --> 38:52.000
Uncle Fraser said that you know the legend.

38:52.000 --> 38:53.000
Oh, yes.

38:53.000 --> 38:55.000
I know the legend.

38:55.000 --> 39:00.000
It's your magic eyes that woke Kendra from his sleep, and now he wants to help.

39:00.000 --> 39:05.000
The legend says that Kendra will come back when he is really needed.

39:05.000 --> 39:08.000
You need him, Lassie, don't you?

39:08.000 --> 39:10.000
I know it.

39:10.000 --> 39:13.000
Yes, I said softly.

39:13.000 --> 39:20.000
Touch the unicorn, and you can have whatever wish your heart desires.

39:20.000 --> 39:26.000
Dolores McTagity took us to the door, and she brushed my face with her hand.

39:26.000 --> 39:34.000
Go, Lassie, and find Kendra.

39:34.000 --> 39:40.000
Chapter 8 The Full Moon

39:40.000 --> 39:44.000
There's a full moon tonight, and the weather's warm.

39:44.000 --> 39:47.000
Let's have a barbecue on the beach.

39:47.000 --> 39:49.000
Said Uncle Fraser.

39:49.000 --> 39:53.000
That's a great idea, I said.

39:53.000 --> 39:56.000
We can collect wood and build a fire.

39:56.000 --> 39:59.000
I've got potatoes and hamburgers.

39:59.000 --> 40:03.000
I went to the butchers in portrait this morning.

40:03.000 --> 40:07.000
Uncle Fraser said as he went down into the cellar.

40:07.000 --> 40:10.000
I sent Mama text message.

40:10.000 --> 40:12.000
How are you?

40:12.000 --> 40:15.000
I love you, Meghan.

40:15.000 --> 40:20.000
I waited, but she didn't reply, so I phoned.

40:20.000 --> 40:23.000
Mrs. Brown answered the phone.

40:23.000 --> 40:26.000
Her voice was sad.

40:26.000 --> 40:28.000
The doctor's here, Meghan.

40:28.000 --> 40:31.000
Your mum's not well at all.

40:31.000 --> 40:33.000
I'll ring you later.

40:33.000 --> 40:41.000
I bit my lip, but the tears still fell, and I went outside to talk to Dolly.

40:41.000 --> 40:46.000
I put my face in her mane until I felt better.

40:46.000 --> 40:49.000
Kendra, where are you?

40:49.000 --> 40:52.000
I said to the wind.

40:52.000 --> 40:59.000
Before the sunset, Ben, Uncle Fraser and I carried our baskets of food to the beach.

40:59.000 --> 41:04.000
We collected firewood, and soon we had a big fire.

41:04.000 --> 41:09.000
The flames jumped, and we had a wonderful barbecue.

41:09.000 --> 41:14.000
The moon came out full and bright, and we sang round the fire.

41:14.000 --> 41:17.000
Uncle Fraser wore his kilt.

41:17.000 --> 41:24.000
He brought his bagpipes and his accordion, and played us some bagpike music first.

41:24.000 --> 41:26.000
He was really good.

41:26.000 --> 41:32.000
Then Uncle Fraser played his accordion, and Ben showed me some Scottish dancing.

41:32.000 --> 41:37.000
It was wonderful, and I laughed and clapped my hands.

41:37.000 --> 41:40.000
Then we sang all the songs we knew.

41:41.000 --> 41:50.000
It was when we started singing the Skyboat song that I saw something silvery white galloping towards us.

41:50.000 --> 41:53.000
Kendra! It's Kendra!

41:53.000 --> 42:00.000
I shouted, and I started to run towards the unicorn, my unicorn, the last unicorn.

42:00.000 --> 42:02.000
Wait for me!

42:02.000 --> 42:06.000
Shouted Ben, but I couldn't hear him.

42:06.000 --> 42:09.000
The unicorn was close now.

42:09.000 --> 42:14.000
I'd see the horn in the middle of its forehead, and its silvery mane.

42:14.000 --> 42:18.000
And then it stopped, and stood quite still.

42:18.000 --> 42:26.000
Its dark brown eyes looked into mine, and it made a soft sound.

42:26.000 --> 42:30.000
Slowly, I went up to the unicorn.

42:30.000 --> 42:37.000
I touched its velvet nose, brushed its neck, and its silken mane.

42:37.000 --> 42:42.000
Make a wish came a thousand whispers.

42:42.000 --> 42:46.000
Make a wish.

42:46.000 --> 42:49.000
I thought of the bullies at school.

42:49.000 --> 42:56.000
I wanted them to leave me alone, but there was something far more important.

42:56.000 --> 43:02.000
I touched the unicorn's horn and made a wish.

43:03.000 --> 43:08.000
The moon shone brighter, and suddenly I was alone.

43:08.000 --> 43:14.000
Kendra was galloping away, out, out to sea.

43:17.000 --> 43:20.000
Listening activity.

43:20.000 --> 43:23.000
Example.

43:24.000 --> 43:27.000
What time are we going to the beach?

43:27.000 --> 43:34.000
Well, it gets dark at about ten o'clock, and we need to build our bonfire.

43:34.000 --> 43:39.000
People walking with their dogs go home at about seven p.m.

43:39.000 --> 43:43.000
So we could be there at seven thirty.

43:43.000 --> 43:46.000
One.

43:46.000 --> 43:53.000
We can cook potatoes in the fire, and hamburgers in a pan on the fire.

43:53.000 --> 43:56.000
Have you got any chocolate cakes?

43:56.000 --> 44:00.000
No, I haven't, but there are strawberry cakes.

44:00.000 --> 44:02.000
I can bring those.

44:02.000 --> 44:05.000
Good. Have you got any orange juice?

44:05.000 --> 44:10.000
No, I've got lemonade. I can bring that.

44:10.000 --> 44:13.000
Two.

44:13.000 --> 44:18.000
Usually, the meat at the butchers is rarely expensive.

44:18.000 --> 44:25.000
The hamburgers usually cost about four pounds, but they are having a special barbecue sale.

44:25.000 --> 44:32.000
The hamburgers were two pounds fifty, so I was pleased.

44:32.000 --> 44:35.000
Three.

44:35.000 --> 44:41.000
I wanted to buy a newspaper, but they had sold out in the village shop.

44:41.000 --> 44:47.000
Duncan, who owns the pub, said I could have his, so I didn't look for newspapers

44:47.000 --> 44:50.000
in the gift shop.

44:50.000 --> 44:52.000
Four.

44:52.000 --> 44:55.000
Where shall we build the bonfire?

44:55.000 --> 45:01.000
We can't build it near the houses or near the trees.

45:01.000 --> 45:10.000
The best possession is between the rocks and the sea.

45:10.000 --> 45:14.000
Scottish music.

45:14.000 --> 45:19.000
Scottish music is unique, and it is famous all over the world.

45:19.000 --> 45:26.000
In the past, the Highlanders used music, dancing and storytelling as entertainment.

45:26.000 --> 45:29.000
They made their own instruments.

45:29.000 --> 45:32.000
Baudrons.

45:32.000 --> 45:38.000
They are simple drums of goat skin, pulled over a round wooden frame.

45:38.000 --> 45:42.000
They used them to accompany the Highlanders into fierce battles,

45:42.000 --> 45:47.000
because the sound they made motivated the men.

45:47.000 --> 45:50.000
Bagpipes.

45:50.000 --> 45:54.000
Bagpipes are among the oldest musical instruments.

45:54.000 --> 46:00.000
The pipes, as they are often called, date back to 100 CE.

46:00.000 --> 46:04.000
Medieval bagpipes were made from natural materials.

46:04.000 --> 46:10.000
There was a windbag, made of sheepskin, a wooden pipe fulfilling the bag with air,

46:10.000 --> 46:15.000
and a flute pipe, which the piper used to make the notes.

46:15.000 --> 46:19.000
The sound came through pipes attached to the bag.

46:19.000 --> 46:26.000
The bagpipes became popular during the 15th century, as musical instruments of war.

46:26.000 --> 46:31.000
Whenever a clan went into battle, the pipers accompanied the men

46:31.000 --> 46:37.000
and used their sound to raise the spirits of their clan and frighten the enemy.

46:37.000 --> 46:42.000
The sound of the pipes and the war cries of the kilted soldiers of the north

46:42.000 --> 46:45.000
frightened the hearts of English soldiers.

46:45.000 --> 46:51.000
After the Jacobite rising in the 18th century and the Battle of Colaudin,

46:51.000 --> 46:57.000
the English banned bagpipes because they were considered an instrument of war.

46:57.000 --> 47:00.000
They also banned kilts.

47:00.000 --> 47:03.000
The Highland Fiddle.

47:03.000 --> 47:09.000
A fiddle and a violin are identical, but the music they play is different.

47:09.000 --> 47:15.000
A violin plays classical music, and a fiddle plays folk music.

47:15.000 --> 47:21.000
The fiddle is used in the highlands to play reels for Highland dancing.

47:21.000 --> 47:23.000
Faden.

47:23.000 --> 47:28.000
In the Celtic world, whistles date back to the 11th century.

47:29.000 --> 47:34.000
Thedons were simple, six-holmed whistles, and they played them by blowing

47:34.000 --> 47:38.000
through a mouthpiece which was made of clay.

47:38.000 --> 47:41.000
The Gaelic harp.

47:41.000 --> 47:45.000
The Gaelic harp is one of the harps to survive from medieval times,

47:45.000 --> 47:48.000
and it was made on the west of Scotland.

47:48.000 --> 47:55.000
It had 32 strings, was made of wood, and was about 95 centimetres high.

47:55.000 --> 48:01.000
It was an aristocratic instrument and was played before the chiefs of clans.

48:01.000 --> 48:06.000
A harp music was transmitted orally from teacher to student.

48:06.000 --> 48:08.000
Cayley.

48:08.000 --> 48:14.000
It is pronounced Cayley and comes from a Gaelic word which means visit.

48:14.000 --> 48:20.000
It is a social event, an evening of traditional Scottish dancing and music.

48:20.000 --> 48:30.000
In the highlands of Scotland, they are usually more concerts than dancing events.

48:30.000 --> 48:32.000
Chapter 9.

48:32.000 --> 48:36.000
It's not goodbye.

48:36.000 --> 48:39.000
The bright sunlight woke me up.

48:39.000 --> 48:45.000
It was late, and I had slept deeply, and I felt happy, really happy

48:45.000 --> 48:48.000
for the first time in a long while.

48:48.000 --> 48:54.000
PHONE RINGS

48:54.000 --> 48:57.000
My mobile phone rang and I jumped out of bed.

48:57.000 --> 48:59.000
Where was it?

48:59.000 --> 49:02.000
I didn't use it very much at the craft.

49:02.000 --> 49:08.000
I had so many other things to do, and phones and televisions were no longer important.

49:08.000 --> 49:13.000
I looked under my clothes and found it in the pocket of my jeans.

49:13.000 --> 49:15.000
Hello?

49:15.000 --> 49:18.000
Meghan, it's Mrs. Brown.

49:18.000 --> 49:22.000
Dr. Barnes is here and he wants to speak to you.

49:22.000 --> 49:24.000
I felt cold.

49:24.000 --> 49:27.000
Did he want to tell me something terrible?

49:27.000 --> 49:29.000
Good morning, Meghan.

49:29.000 --> 49:31.000
Came his loud voice.

49:31.000 --> 49:35.000
I have good news, great news.

49:35.000 --> 49:38.000
Yesterday evening your mother was very ill.

49:38.000 --> 49:40.000
I didn't know what to do.

49:40.000 --> 49:45.000
She had a high temperature, and Mrs. Brown and I sat with her.

49:45.000 --> 49:51.000
Then, suddenly, at about midnight, she sat up in bed and said,

49:51.000 --> 49:53.000
I feel better.

49:53.000 --> 49:56.000
Could I have a cup of tea and a slice of toast, please?

49:56.000 --> 49:59.000
Her temperature was normal.

49:59.000 --> 50:01.000
It's a miracle, Meghan.

50:01.000 --> 50:02.000
A miracle.

50:02.000 --> 50:06.000
I ran downstairs to tell Uncle Fraser.

50:06.000 --> 50:09.000
The unicorn, he gave me a wish.

50:09.000 --> 50:14.000
Mum's better, and it was Kendra's wish that made her well.

50:14.000 --> 50:20.000
My uncle turned and walked over to the window and looked out at the sea.

50:20.000 --> 50:22.000
I left him alone.

50:22.000 --> 50:25.000
He didn't want me to see his tears of happiness.

50:25.000 --> 50:28.000
I went outside with Idris.

50:28.000 --> 50:31.000
Ben was there with Dolly and Moon.

50:31.000 --> 50:37.000
He helped me to get on Dolly, and as we took the path that led down to the sea,

50:37.000 --> 50:40.000
I told him about Mum and Kendra's wish.

50:40.000 --> 50:45.000
What will he do about the bullies at school when you go back, Meghan?

50:45.000 --> 50:47.000
He asked.

50:47.000 --> 50:52.000
I'll speak to Mum when she's completely better, and to a teacher at school.

50:52.000 --> 50:54.000
It will be all right.

50:54.000 --> 50:57.000
I want you to come and visit me in London.

50:57.000 --> 51:00.000
I'll miss you, I said.

51:00.000 --> 51:02.000
I'll miss you more.

51:02.000 --> 51:03.000
Said Ben.

51:03.000 --> 51:07.000
A month on Sky passed so quickly.

51:07.000 --> 51:09.000
I wanted to see Mum.

51:09.000 --> 51:15.000
But I didn't want to leave Ben, Uncle Fraser, the ponies and Idris.

51:15.000 --> 51:18.000
Ben and Uncle Fraser looked at each other.

51:18.000 --> 51:21.000
It was a secret look.

51:21.000 --> 51:26.000
Meghan, you can't take Idris or Dolly back home.

51:26.000 --> 51:29.000
So we have a present for you.

51:29.000 --> 51:31.000
Said Uncle Fraser.

51:31.000 --> 51:34.000
It's outside in the trap.

51:34.000 --> 51:39.000
Dolores McTagity gave it to me, and she thinks you will be happy together.

51:39.000 --> 51:45.000
Sitting on my suitcase was a beautiful cocker spaniel puppy.

51:45.000 --> 51:48.000
Thank you, I said, and I hugged them.

51:48.000 --> 51:53.000
She's beautiful, but I don't want to leave you.

51:53.000 --> 51:58.000
We can write and speak on the phone, and you can come back soon.

51:58.000 --> 52:00.000
Said Ben.

52:00.000 --> 52:02.000
Come back with my sister.

52:02.000 --> 52:06.000
Uncle Fraser said, as he kissed my cheek.

52:06.000 --> 52:08.000
Come for a new year.

52:08.000 --> 52:10.000
We call it Hogmanee in Scotland.

52:10.000 --> 52:13.000
We have wonderful celebrations in the village.

52:13.000 --> 52:18.000
There is a custom here which brings good luck for the coming year.

52:18.000 --> 52:24.000
When the clock strikes midnight, some of us from the village go to Betty McAllister's house.

52:24.000 --> 52:28.000
A piece of bread, some money, and some coal.

52:28.000 --> 52:31.000
All these things bring good luck.

52:31.000 --> 52:34.000
The coal is so that the house is always warm.

52:34.000 --> 52:41.000
The bread is so there is always food to eat, and the money so that there is always money.

52:41.000 --> 52:45.000
Then we throw ashes out of the back door.

52:45.000 --> 52:48.000
Why do you do that, I asked?

52:48.000 --> 52:51.000
It's the old year leaving.

52:51.000 --> 52:53.000
Continued Uncle Fraser.

52:53.000 --> 52:55.000
Then we have a party.

52:55.000 --> 52:56.000
Said Ben.

52:56.000 --> 52:58.000
My uncle smiled.

52:58.000 --> 53:00.000
A fine party.

53:00.000 --> 53:01.000
He said.

53:01.000 --> 53:04.000
We sing and dance until morning.

53:04.000 --> 53:06.000
Do come, Megan.

53:06.000 --> 53:08.000
I looked at them.

53:08.000 --> 53:12.000
Hogmanee on Skye and Betty McAllister's party.

53:12.000 --> 53:17.000
Singing songs around the piano with Uncle Fraser, Ben and Mum.

53:17.000 --> 53:21.000
I wanted this more than anything else in the world.

53:21.000 --> 53:26.000
Yes, I said, and I hugged my uncle again.

53:26.000 --> 53:28.000
Then it was time to go.

53:28.000 --> 53:35.000
We rode in the trap to Armadale, and when we passed the ruined castle, I thought I saw

53:35.000 --> 53:41.000
a silvery white horse arching its neck and galloping in the waves.

53:41.000 --> 53:43.000
Goodbye, Kendra.

53:43.000 --> 53:45.000
I whispered.

53:45.000 --> 53:50.000
And on the salty air there came a cry, as the little white horse called out to me.

53:50.000 --> 53:54.000
Of course, we knew this was not goodbye.

